Real-world use cases (AI/ML, hybrid apps, data platforms)

🏗️ Cluster Management
eksctl create cluster --name myCluster --region us-east-1 --nodes 3 → Create a new EKS cluster

eksctl get cluster → List all clusters

eksctl delete cluster --name myCluster → Delete a cluster

aws eks update-kubeconfig --region us-east-1 --name myCluster → Update kubeconfig to connect kubectl to EKS

📦 Node Group Management
eksctl create nodegroup --cluster myCluster --name ng1 --nodes 3 → Add a node group

eksctl get nodegroup --cluster myCluster → List node groups

eksctl delete nodegroup --cluster myCluster --name ng1 → Remove a node group

🌐 Deployments & Services (via kubectl)
kubectl apply -f deployment.yaml → Deploy workloads

kubectl get pods -n mynamespace → List pods in a namespace

kubectl get svc → List services

kubectl describe svc myservice → Inspect service details

🔍 Monitoring & Debugging
kubectl logs <pod-name> → View pod logs

kubectl exec -it <pod-name> -- bash → Open shell inside pod

kubectl get events → Show cluster events

kubectl top nodes → Resource usage of nodes

kubectl top pods → Resource usage of pods

⚙️ Scaling & Updates
kubectl scale deployment myapp --replicas=5 → Scale pods

kubectl rollout status deployment/myapp → Check rollout progress

kubectl rollout undo deployment/myapp → Rollback deployment

🗣️ Interview Narration Tip

“In real projects, I use eksctl for cluster and node group management, and kubectl for deployments, scaling, and debugging. The combination of these commands covers the full lifecycle of EKS workloads.”

✅ Bottom Line:  
EKS commands are a mix of eksctl (cluster/node ops) and kubectl (workload ops). Together, they let you create, manage, scale, and troubleshoot Kubernetes clusters on AWS.

